"1120","1175":"1175","1085":"1085","Saint-Maixent-sur-Vie, Vendée, Pays de la Loire, France":"Saint-Maixent-sur-Vie, Vendée, Frankrijk","Dax,40088,Landes,Nouvelle-Aquitaine,FRANCE,":"Dax, Landes, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Frankrijk"},"en":{"ABT 1110–ABT 1175":"about 1110–about 1175","1110–1175":"1110–1175","1120–Female":"1120–Deceased","1120–1145":"1120–1145","–Male":"Deceased","1145–Male":"1145–Deceased","1085–Male":"1085–Deceased","1090–Female":"1090–Deceased","1090":"1090","AFT 1145":"after 1145","ABT 1175":"about 1175","ABT 1110":"about 1110","1145":"1145","1110":"1110","1120":"1120","1175":"1175","1085":"1085","Saint-Maixent-sur-Vie, Vendée, Pays de la Loire, France":"Saint-Maixent-sur-Vie, Vendée, France","Dax,40088,Landes,Nouvelle-Aquitaine,FRANCE,":"Dax, Landes, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"PAREDS","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Carlos, Manuel, Luis, Miguel, Jorge, Francisco, Mario, Pedro, Roberto, Ernesto.","Spanish, Galician, and Portuguese: topographic name from Spanish <i>pared</i>, Portuguese and Galician <i>parede</i> ‘(house) wall’. The surname may be for a person who lived in a lean-to built against the wall of a larger building (servants often lived in buildings of this sort outside manor houses), or for a person from any of numerous places called with this word."],"variants":[{"name":"Paredez","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Eleno, Manuel, Armando, Carlos, Jose, Juan, Lupe, Pedro, Alfredo, Benito, Blanca, Cruz.","Hispanic: altered form of Spanish, Galician, and Portuguese   Paredes  ."]}]},{"name":"Aymery","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin):","from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Amalric</i>, composed of the elements <i>Amal</i> (a dynastic name among the Goths) + <i>rīk</i> ‘realm, power’. The name was introduced into England from France by the Normans, developing into the Middle English personal name <i>Amery</i>, <i>Emery</i> (from Old French <i>Amauri</i>, <i>Emaurri</i>).","occasionally perhaps also from the Middle English, Old French personal name <i>Aimery</i>, ancient Germanic <i>Haimeric</i>, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’+ <i>rīc</i> ‘power(ful)’. Compare   Emery  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Amber","meanings":["From the word for the fossilized resin <i>amber</i>, a word derived via Old French and Latin from Arabic <i>ambar</i>. This was first used as a given name at the end of the 19th century. It enjoyed a surge in popularity following the publication of  Kathleen Winsor's  novel Forever Amber in  1944 , and again in the 1990s."]},{"name":"Hembree","meanings":["Altered form of English <b>Hembrey</b>, a variant of   Amery  , with excrescent <i>H-</i>."]},{"name":"Armey","meanings":["Altered form of English   Amery  ."]},{"name":"Emery","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, derived in the Middle Ages from a personal name introduced to England by the Normans. This was originally composed of the Germanic elements <i>amal</i> ‘bravery, vigour’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power’, but soon assumed a variety of forms such as <i>Amauri</i> and <i>Emauri</i>."]}]}],"lifeSummary"